SIMPLE: commotion
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Commotion
<hw>Com*mo"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>commotio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>commotion</ets>. See
<er>Motion</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Disturbed or violent motion;
agitation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[What] <qex>commotion</qex> in the winds !</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A popular tumult; public disturbance;
riot.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When ye shall hear of wars and <qex>commotions</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Luke xxi. 9.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Agitation, perturbation, or disorder, of mind; heat;
excitement.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧He could not debate anything without some
<xex>commotion</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Clarendon.</au></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Excitement; agitation; perturbation; disturbance;
tumult; disorder; violence.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Commove</ent>⟦br⟧
